Sta. Maria Hill in Daraga, Albay is one of the best and safest places to view the Mayon Volcano, seen in the background seemingly calm.
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (PHIVOLCS) described it as the "calm before the storm" since it expects the volcano to erupt within the next few days.

The Nuestra Se√±ora de la Porteria (Our Lady of the Gate) is located on the hill. According to the National Center for Culture and the Arts, the church is the oldest existing structure in the province, built in 1772, and is an example of Filipino baroque architecture.

Photo courtesy of Bicolano Man

June is traditionally known as the wedding month, but times have changed. Records today show that most Filipinos tie the knot, perhaps more appropriately, in February, which has always been celebrated as the love month. 

As old as mankind, as legendary as the Holy Grail, and as complex as the origin of the universe, love is the one emotion that almost always defies logic and pushes people to the extreme. Why do women fall for womanizers? Why do husbands go astray? Why do people fall in love and kill for love? 

Questions about love, falling in and out of love, are endless, much like its very definition.
In keeping with tradition, Cheche Lazaro Presents unravels this June the mystery of love through its ultimate manifestation -- marriage.

Broadcast journalist Cheche Lazaro takes a deeper look into the happy-ever-after promise ‚Äì or goal -- of marriage and the very complexity of love as a science. Sharing their own experiences are celebrity couples Christian and Winnie Monsod, who have been together for 53 years, and newlyweds Boots Anson Roa and Francisco "King" Rodrigo, who are at it a second time.

Psychiatrist Ma. Luz Querubin, anthropologist Jonathan Taduran, and human sexuality expert and psychologist Agnes Bueno discuss the science and explain why the heart is the wrong symbolism for love. They redefine the common perceptions of love and explain how chemical processes in the brain ‚Äì and our sense of smell -- can lead to falling in love.

Love advice expert Papa Jack and marriage councilor Pastor Herald Cruz provide the healthy boost on the intricacies of marriage and love.

This two-hour documentary special is a testimony of timeless, endless love bound by the sacrament of marriage. It is a road map to a bumpy and challenging but worth-keeping relationships as well.

Kapag Tumibok Ang Puso is not for the loveless to seek love or for those who are in love to veer away from it. It is for those who see, feel and know how it is to love, those who are willing to love and be loved.

Fall and stay in love this June 22 on "Cheche Lazaro Presents: Kapag Tumibok Ang Puso" on ABS-CBN Sunday's Best.

INFOGRAPHIC: Are our firefighters equipped to fight fires?

http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/metro-manila/03/18/14/infographic-are-our-firefighters-equipped-fight-fires

A Commission on Audit (COA) report in 2012 once again puts the spotlight on our ill-equipped Bureau of Fire Protection (BFP). Thousands of firefighters go about their dangerous task every day without fire coats, trousers, gloves, boots and helmets. Nearly a fourth of our municipalities, cities and provinces do not have fire stations.

As the COA report says, unless the BFP's firefighting equipment and facilities are modernized, its mandate of keeping our homes and communities safe is far from being realized.

The largest hotel in Macau to date boasts of nearly 4,000 guestrooms and suites spread over two towers.

How do you fit more than 70,000 evacuees in one space?

And that is just for starters. Can you imagine feeding 70,000 people, even by batches of a thousand, 3 times a day? Where do they sleep? Where do they bathe? Where do they defecate? 

The Zamboanga siege may be a military and economic crisis for the city of Zamboanga, but for the 70,000 souls who have nowhere to go, it has become a humanitarian crisis.

International aid groups define a humanitarian crisis as an event or series of events which represents a critical threat to the health, safety, security or well-being of a community or other large group of people that extends beyond the mandate or capacity of any single agency.

Here are images of the humanitarian crisis taken by ABS-CBNnews.com photographer, Rem Zamora.

---
This photo shows how the 1935 Constitution of the Philippines came to be.

*Photo and description source: Official Tumblr Page of the Presidential Museum and Library (Public Domain)

On March 25, 1935, United States President Franklin D. Roosevelt certified the draft constitution submitted by the Constitutional Convention of 1934.

Thereafter, the Filipino people voted to ratify this draft, through a plebiscite held on May 14, 1935.

SLIDESHOW: The high cost of war in Zamboanga
http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/09/16/13/slideshow-zamboanga-crisis-continues

Burned neighborhoods. Broken spirits. Lost lives.

Nine days of fighting in Zamboanga have left an indelible mark in the city that was once called a "city of love."

While many breathed a sigh of relief as dozens of hostages were secured from the conflict areas, a few stared off at a distance as they pondered what steps to take next.

For the soldiers, the war is not yet over and tougher days might still be ahead as they continue to hunt down the MNLF rebels .

For the residents of Zamboanga whose houses were destroyed, they would have to start again, hopefully, with a lot of help from the government and the private sector.

For the hostages who were caught in the crossfire, the sound of gunfire will likely linger in their memories.

Although the conflict appears to be nearing its end in Zamboanga, the cycle of violence has turned once again, making the road to peace in Muslim Mindanao more challenging and difficult.

http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/lifestyle/09/19/12/slideshow-hunks-strip-cosmo-bash

While Paulo Avelino was supposed to headline the annual show dubbed as a "shameless objectification of men," the "Walang Hanggan" actor was nowhere in sight, much to the dismay of the crowd.

status_message:
In 2007, 17-year-old Bonita Baran came to Manila to work as a household helper for the Marzan family. Even with a starting salary of only P700 a month, things worked out fine in the beginning between Bonita and her employers Reynold and Annaliza Marzan.

By Bonita's accounts, the harrowing experiences started in 2008 when she would get beaten by Annaliza whenever she makes mistakes. The beatings became more frequent and turned more violent as the years went by, but Bonita could not get out of it.

Finally, in 2012, with almost every inch of her body battered and her sight almost completely gone, Bonita was allowed to go home to her family in the province. The Marzans have denied Bonita's allegations.

Here is her story.

http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/lifestyle/08/28/12/slideshow-farewell-jesse

After 6 days of national mourning, Interior and Local Government Secretary Jesse Robredo was given a state funeral and was laid to rest in his "happy place" of Naga City, where he served as mayor for 18 years.

Excerpts from the homily of Fr. Kulandairaj Ambrose, MOP at the funeral mass for Sec. Jesse Robredo:

"Sec. Jesse Robredo was a man of compassion for the poor, the needy, and everyone. Leaders must have a vision and will. He had both, and completed his mission.

Jesse made everyone feel wanted. He simply treated everyone with respect.  

He had time for everybody except himself. 

Seldom do people pass away doing what they loved doing. Jesse passed away doing what he loved most: going home.

Jesse was not a perfect human being but he was a true human being who treated everyone as true as himself.

You have fared well in this life. Fare well in the next. Maraming salamat Jesse for being a true friend of the common people.

Ingat po. Dios Mabalos!"

Earlier, Grace Ibuna, the late Rep. Iggy Arroyo's partner, was on ANC 24/7 Headstart.

Ibuna on people calling her a mistress and saying bad things about her: "I am not a mistress nor am I a whore. They should go back and start reading the dictionary."

Ibuna said believes she is not a home wrecker. "How can you wreck something that was wrecked already?" 

Ibuna on Aleli Arroyo, Iggy's legal wife: Aleli is not even the first wife. Para kaming "Mano Po." The way she speaks, she's so righteous. Baka magkaiba kami ng Bible na binabasa.

Q: Was there anything for Aleli?
Ibuna: None.

Q: Did Iggy hate Aleli?
Ibuna: Abhor is the word for it.

Q: Did Iggy leave anything to his daughter with Aleli? 
Ibuna: Yes, and I intend to honor (his commitments to his children).

Ibuna on marriage: I believe in marriage but let's face the truth: kung hindi na kayo masaya, bakit pa?

For more quotes from Karen Davila's interview with Grace Ibuna, follow @abscbnnews or @ancalerts on Twitter.

Azkals made history by advancing to the semis of the 2012 Challenge Cup with a 2-1 drubbing of Tajikistan. #challengecup

#CJonTrial updates as of 4:45pm:

Demetrio C. Vicente has been called to the witness stand. He is testifying on the sale of seven parcels of land to him by Mrs. Corona.

Vicente is Chief Justice Renato Corona's second cousin. (His middle name is Coronado.)

Questioning revolving on tax payments and deeds of sale; Vicente said the title and absolute deed of sale is with him. However, the land is not registered in his name, so he is paying real estate taxes in Mrs. Corona's name.

Another interesting development: The prosecution raised the possibility that Vicente's deed of sale was not notarized by a registered notary. They showed a certification that the notary was not licensed in Makati City. Vicente was accompanied to the notary by Mrs. Corona.

Vicente, however, asserted that the land is his, and he has been the one paying taxes on it since he bought it in 1990.

Vicente still on the stand, recess called for the sound system in the Senate session hall to be fixed.

For more updates, see our #CJontrial portal http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/cjontrial

Day 28 of #CJonTrial - Highlights as of 3:15pm:

Rep. Tobias "Toby" Tiangco was questioned by Senator-judge Miriam Defensor Santiago on what his motivation was in testifying. Tiangco said he only wanted to prove he is telling the truth, to which Santiago responded he is "too good to be true."

Tiangco said he will not run for Senator, but will run for reelection in Navotas after he finishes his current term. He can run for two more terms. 

Memorable dialogue:
Tiangco: It's nothing personal. I don't want to offend anyone.
Santiago: Feel free to offend me if you want to.

Santiago to Tiangco: You'll end up either a hero in the public's eyes or a traitor in the eyes of your colleagues.

**

The defense's next witness was Araceli Bayuga, the Supreme Court's Chief Judicial Staff Officer. Bayuga is in charge of cash collection and disbursement in the SC. Her department handles compensation and taxation for SC employees, including the Chief Justice.

Bayuga presented alpha lists containing tax payment records of CJ Renato Corona from 2002-2005. She also presented a list of Corona's salaries from 2002-2011. 

According to a tweet by @Karen_Davila, "Bayuga (enumerates ALL allowances of CJ Corona) - all paid payrolls of CJ Corona 2002-2011 - P21,636,781.45."

Bayuga said aside from his salary, Corona incurred benefits such as for good productivity, rice allowance, Christmas bonus, etc.

Defense ends questioning of Bayuga. Prosecution to conduct cross examination tomorrow, will go over docs presented by defense.
The Corona impeachment trial has started. 19 senator-judges present.

(UPDATE) The NKTI, in a medical bulletin, said that Boncodin died at 2:05 p.m. due to cardiac arrest. She was 55. She was admitted to the hospital last March 10 due to difficulty of breathing and anemia. She was diagnosed to be on last stage of renal disease after her kidney transplant on February 2005. She went into chronic rejection and her kidney has completely failed to function.
Former Budget Secretary Emilia Boncodin passed away on Monday. Boncodin died at around 1 p.m. at the National Kidney and Transplant Institute (NKTI) after a long battle with multiple kidney cysts.

status_message: Live chat will be extended for the 2010 poll automation forum. Drop your opinions on http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/ancliveevents
Rafanan (Comelec): Dapat nakasulat sa registration form na hindi siya (voter) marunong magbasa at sumulat. Kung hindi, hindi siya pwedeng i-assist.
Roxas-Chua: If you make it a pin, it's easier to sell the ballots.
Tabunda (PulseAsia): What happens to the unused ballots?

Smartmatic: Don't use liquid paper because you might tamper the unit. Do not leave marks, like masking tape, in the ballots because when the machine gets opened, there's no assurance that it is the voter who put the mark. Think ahead on who you're going to vote for.

Smartmatic: The machine has 2 back-up memories sealed in the machine. If anything wrong happens, we can bring a back-up machine to the precinct, synchronize the new machine and continue the voting procedure.
Roxas-Chua: The only thing that will be rejected by the machine are fake ballots.

Roxas-Chua: There will be tests for the codes. With regards to hacking, these machines will not be online during the day and will only be online while transmitting, which will only take a very short time.
Roxas-Chua: These machines have batteries that can last for 2 days of election. If it fails, we can always go back to manual counting.
Virtus Gil asks speakers: What will you do in cases of network failure, power breakdown, hacking, and preloaded machines?
Mara: Not because it works in Canada or in another part of the world, it will work in the Philippines.
Smartmatic: In the US, every county is independent in the machine they use. The specific case of 2000 Florida elections, those were ballots that need to be punched--a very different system.
ANC's 2010 poll automation forum is ongoing. Watch the free livestream by logging on to http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/ancliveevents
Smartmatic: In minutes you could check if the results that were printed (election returns) coincides with what was published in the website.
Smartmatic: The machine will tabulate the results in 20 to 30 seconds--a procedure that would have taken 5 to 6 hours.

Smartmatic: Let's calibrate the system so we know for sure that this is not fingermarks. If there are overvotes, that certain part will be invalidated by the machine but the rest of the votes will be counted.
Smartmatic: The ballot can be inserted in any position: face up, face down, bottoms first. Voters are supposed to not hold into anything after feeding the ballot. The ballots stay inside the machine.
Boto Patrollers trying out the machine. Watch the free livestream by logging on to http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/ancliveevents
Machine demonstration airing now at ANC. Watch the free livestream by logging on to http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/ancliveevents
Rafanan (Comelec): Each ballot will be more or less two feet long.
Rafanan to demonstrate how the machine works. Watch the free livestream by logging on to http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/ancliveevents
Rafanan (Comelec): Magkakaron ng massive voter's education and information try sa mga schools, etc.
#ancforum - for those with Twitter accounts, you can use this hash key to participate in the ANC Poll Automation live chat event on abs-cbnNEWS.com
ANC's 2010 poll automation forum is ongoing. Watch the free livestream by logging on to http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/ancliveevents
Gregorio (Smartmatic): We don't have a say on where to put the machine, it's Comelec's sovereign decision. One we get the location from Comelec, we have a software to monitor the machines.
Gregorio (Smartmatic): The key is how to fill up the ballot because the interaction with the machine is minimum.
Calleja (PPCRV): May baterya ang machine, walang brown-out, walang black-out, walang failure of elections.
Rafanan: General instructions will come out soon. Kapag lumabas ng October, maaga yan. We are just coming up with some of the things to be customized.
Rafanan (Comelec): In 2013 elections we will be using the fingerprint identification machine. We are paying P1.6 billion for that machine.
Rafanan: Because we saved money from the machine, we might use the money to buy and display security cameras in certain precincts.
Rafanan (Comelec): The law does not use the term pilot test. There is really no such thing as pilot testing of the automation system. SC ruled that testing is not a prerequisite.

Gregorio (Smartmatic): Results are directly transmitted to the machines from the municipal level, then to the provincial, then to the national level. A copy of the results are published in the website.
